Language plays a crucial role in shaping human thought. It allows us to communicate our ideas, feelings, and experiences to others, and it also shapes the way we think about and understand the world. Research has shown that the language we speak can influence our perception, memory, and even our decision-making.

One research example that illustrates the role of language in shaping thought is the study of linguistic relativity, also known as the Whorfian hypothesis. This hypothesis suggests that the language we speak shapes the way we think and perceive the world. One famous study that supports this idea is the research on color perception by Eleanor Rosch and her colleagues in the 1970s. They found that English speakers, who have words for 11 basic colors, have a harder time distinguishing between similar shades of blue and green than do speakers of some indigenous languages, who have words for many more shades of these colors. This suggests that the language we speak can shape the way we perceive and think about colors.

In conclusion, research has shown that language plays a crucial role in shaping human thought. The language we speak shapes the way we perceive, think and understand the world. The study of linguistic relativity, and in particular the study of color perception by Eleanor Rosch, provides an example of how the language we speak shapes our thought process.

